1
00:00:01,076 --> 00:00:30,307
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:31,181 --> 00:00:35,792
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:45,677 --> 00:01:03,651
Every so often I hear about somebody who, just out of the blue, is hit by a sort of mental disturbance, a storm, which drives them to taking tablets.

4
00:01:03,731 --> 00:01:08,900
I mean, it's that bad, some sort of mental illness which seems to arise and then just pass away.

5
00:01:10,787 --> 00:01:17,822
Thinking of a friend who just suddenly out of the blue, a deep depression, took about six, nine months and disappeared.

6
00:01:19,605 --> 00:01:22,070
Still not, hasn't returned.

7
00:01:24,174 --> 00:01:30,787
Whereas others, just in, you know, in the middle of life, you know, even...

8
00:01:30,768 --> 00:01:43,950
After years of what you might call ordinary neurotic living, suddenly they're struck with this really painful mental state, deep anxiety that seems to be uncontrollable.

9
00:01:46,495 --> 00:02:01,010
And if we haven't got a model of how the psyche works, then of course it can add to it an enormous sense of despair.

10
00:02:02,881 --> 00:02:06,165
sort of panic, you know, like, what to do?

11
00:02:07,647 --> 00:02:20,040
And these days we have various models, you know, coming from the psychotherapeutic tradition, which is helpful, no doubt about that.

12
00:02:20,061 --> 00:02:27,689
And there was a time when taking drugs was a real no-no in the Buddhist society because it wasn't facing up to your karma.

13
00:02:29,812 --> 00:02:37,228
So I think people have relented on that a bit and decided that skillful use of drugs can steady somebody.

14
00:02:38,991 --> 00:02:42,759
But even then, it doesn't always work.

15
00:02:45,051 --> 00:02:49,015
I'm just thinking of a friend who was an occasional student.

16
00:02:50,236 --> 00:02:55,242
Again, somewhere around his 40s, you see, suddenly struck by depression.

17
00:02:56,443 --> 00:02:59,627
And the psychiatrist told him it was a type that would recur, which didn't help.

18
00:03:01,650 --> 00:03:03,611
And eventually he got into this state.

19
00:03:03,651 --> 00:03:07,355
When I went to see him, there was no humour in the man.

20
00:03:08,736 --> 00:03:09,277
None whatsoever.

21
00:03:10,859 --> 00:03:14,383
And he was in the habit of, when he was talking to you,

22
00:03:15,004 --> 00:03:17,328
I was always filled with this profound disgust.

23
00:03:18,710 --> 00:03:33,751
And so I said to him, now he's a committed Buddhist, he practiced quite a bit, and he understands that, or I think he held the belief, because he used to say to his sister, that there would be a future life, future karma.

24
00:03:34,412 --> 00:03:37,856
So I asked him, I said, are you contemplating suicide?

25
00:03:39,288 --> 00:03:40,109
He said, no.

26
00:03:41,230 --> 00:03:45,236
Then, of course, a few days later, I hear that he has actually killed himself.

27
00:03:46,598 --> 00:04:00,379
And he downloaded a little mechanism from the websites that creates carbon monoxide and put it in his... drove out to the countryside in his car, set it going, and they found him in a peaceful place.

28
00:04:02,623 --> 00:04:03,405
And...

29
00:04:05,258 --> 00:04:07,421
Obviously things had got to the top of him.

30
00:04:07,502 --> 00:04:08,443
He was taking drugs.

31
00:04:08,463 --> 00:04:09,025
He didn't help.

32
00:04:09,205 --> 00:04:11,991
And he had about six people constantly visiting him.

33
00:04:13,693 --> 00:04:15,617
All the support services came to help him.

34
00:04:15,657 --> 00:04:17,040
His sister was everywhere.

35
00:04:17,060 --> 00:04:19,285
It just became sort of unbearable.

36
00:04:25,559 --> 00:04:41,982
And I think in those sorts of times, unless your practice has grounded you in a psychology, in a model of the mind that allows you to see hope, then it looks pretty dark, you know.

37
00:04:43,704 --> 00:04:46,689
And really that's what we're discovering.

38
00:04:47,228 --> 00:04:54,839
We're discovering that no matter how much physical pain or mental pain there might be,

39
00:04:56,845 --> 00:05:14,262
if we can just hang on in there it will it will dissolve you know or it will kill us but for it to kill us is not the same as for us to kill ourselves

40
00:05:16,132 --> 00:05:32,064
Just to give you one example of where, I mean it's a bit dramatic and it's slightly a bit, it's not the best of examples, but I remember reading in this manual of what happened at the Mahasi centre while the Mahasi was teaching.

41
00:05:33,187 --> 00:05:36,774
And there's a man who went along with stomach cancer.

42
00:05:37,884 --> 00:05:43,372
pretty advanced, they'd given up hope on him, and he stopped taking all the drugs and began to meditate.

43
00:05:43,612 --> 00:05:46,757
And as he expressed it, there was an explosion.

44
00:05:48,079 --> 00:05:48,660
I disappeared.

45
00:05:50,281 --> 00:05:57,952
So this would suggest that the cancer had been caused by a mental imbalance, not by some sort of chemical state.

46
00:05:59,906 --> 00:06:13,786
So our aim really is in the long term to take from the Buddha's teaching some sort of model of the mind which allows us to see this liberation.

47
00:06:17,552 --> 00:06:25,223
And there's, you might say, three parts to the process.

48
00:06:25,826 --> 00:06:31,495
The part is how to deal with all the stuff that comes up which is painful, both physical and mental.

49
00:06:33,377 --> 00:06:44,713
The other part is how to develop a beautiful mind and the third part is how to liberate, liberate us completely

50
00:06:45,706 --> 00:06:50,514
from the possibility of suffering, from the possibility of suffering, and that's his message.

51
00:06:51,937 --> 00:07:02,194
Nibbāna isn't a sort of peaceful wonderful state so long as that doesn't happen, so long as this doesn't happen.

52
00:07:02,896 --> 00:07:08,786
It's complete liberation from the possibility of suffering.

53
00:07:08,805 --> 00:07:11,189
Now the Buddha himself didn't have an easy time.

54
00:07:12,233 --> 00:07:19,404
I mean, apart from the early part where he's, you know, I mean, he's left his family.

55
00:07:19,625 --> 00:07:21,668
I mean, it's not, that can't have been very easy.

56
00:07:22,009 --> 00:07:23,071
Then all that training.

57
00:07:23,951 --> 00:07:28,199
And then there must have been a joyous period where he's teaching and people are gathering around him.

58
00:07:29,440 --> 00:07:33,947
And then towards the end of his life, things go all upside down.

59
00:07:34,610 --> 00:07:36,132
David Hartley tries to kill him.

60
00:07:37,899 --> 00:07:48,774
His two big mates who'd supported him all his life, the two kings of Kosala, Pasenadi and Bimbisara of Magadha, which is around modern day Varanasi, died.

61
00:07:49,394 --> 00:07:59,689
And their sons weren't particularly, I mean, his, the son of Bimbisara, I can't remember his name now, I can't remember his name, no.

62
00:08:00,783 --> 00:08:06,112
He had been in cahoots with this Devadatta and he killed his own father.

63
00:08:06,132 --> 00:08:06,733
He starved him.

64
00:08:07,735 --> 00:08:08,516
Starved him to death.

65
00:08:09,399 --> 00:08:13,266
You can go and see where the building is, if you want, in Rajgir.

66
00:08:14,247 --> 00:08:15,249
At least that's what they say it is.

67
00:08:16,331 --> 00:08:25,187
He starved his father so he could become king and the thing was that Devadatta would get rid of the Buddha and he'd become head of the order and there'd be peace and harmony.

68
00:08:27,310 --> 00:08:35,919
And after all that, when he'd killed, he had a remorse, he had a great remorse, and he went to apologize to the Buddha, confess to him, all that stuff.

69
00:08:35,940 --> 00:08:46,913
But there's no, there's nothing else in the story that I could perceive anyway, that he became as devoted a supporter of the Buddha as his father had been.

70
00:08:46,932 --> 00:08:53,200
And the same with Viduddha, who was the son of the king of Kosala.

71
00:08:53,634 --> 00:09:00,162
The story there is that he'd married into the Buddha's clan.

72
00:09:00,182 --> 00:09:09,071
And because they thought that he was of a lower caste, he wasn't really up to the Sakyas, they palmed him off with a servant girl of a lower caste.

73
00:09:09,770 --> 00:09:12,975
When he found this out, he was justifiably enraged.

74
00:09:14,696 --> 00:09:18,139
And he got his army together, got on his elephant, and off he went to destroy the Sakyas.

75
00:09:19,160 --> 00:09:22,443
So the Buddha went out and had a chat with him.

76
00:09:22,464 --> 00:09:23,085
And he went back.

77
00:09:24,365 --> 00:09:26,508
But you know how it is, it builds up on the mind.

78
00:09:26,548 --> 00:09:29,871
So he got on his elephant again and rode out with his army.

79
00:09:30,511 --> 00:09:33,436
And the Buddha again went to have a little chat.

80
00:09:35,317 --> 00:09:37,100
And he saw the senseless knowledge, so he came back.

81
00:09:38,361 --> 00:09:41,565
And off he went again, got on his elephant, off he went again.

82
00:09:41,644 --> 00:09:47,993
On one part I read it was the third time the Buddha said, I can't do anything, that's it, the karma's too great.

83
00:09:48,783 --> 00:09:49,604
It might have gone out again.

84
00:09:49,663 --> 00:09:50,725
It was the fourth time, he said.

85
00:09:50,804 --> 00:09:53,788
But anyway, there was a point where the Buddha knew he couldn't stop it.

86
00:09:54,208 --> 00:09:54,789
And so he did.

87
00:09:55,711 --> 00:09:57,732
He killed a lot of his people.

88
00:09:57,793 --> 00:09:59,315
They moved capital.

89
00:10:01,518 --> 00:10:02,999
So there he is, this old man.

90
00:10:03,058 --> 00:10:04,441
I mean, he's in his 70s now.

91
00:10:04,480 --> 00:10:06,202
He died by 18.

92
00:10:06,222 --> 00:10:07,524
He's got to handle all this stuff.

93
00:10:08,885 --> 00:10:10,888
And his family's being killed.

94
00:10:10,969 --> 00:10:12,990
And his supporters are going.

95
00:10:13,091 --> 00:10:18,317
And his cousin, Devadatta, whom he's given all this Dharma to, wants to kill him.

96
00:10:20,339 --> 00:10:22,383
It's a heck of a way to end your life, isn't it?

97
00:10:25,168 --> 00:10:36,028
So he wasn't immune from the vicissitudes of life, but nowhere do we get the impression that he's perturbed by it.

98
00:10:38,533 --> 00:10:40,778
It's like this is the way it is.

99
00:10:41,246 --> 00:10:45,893
And he does his best to try and cure the situation.

100
00:10:46,274 --> 00:10:54,924
Like when Devadatta takes off a load of monks, he sends his two chief disciples, Sariputta and Moggallana, to talk to them.

101
00:10:54,945 --> 00:10:56,366
And they bring most of them back.

102
00:10:57,428 --> 00:10:58,649
But Devadatta continues.

103
00:10:58,730 --> 00:11:00,452
He continues as a monk.

104
00:11:02,936 --> 00:11:08,823
So it's this ability to remain equanimous.

105
00:11:10,102 --> 00:11:16,049
That's probably, well, according to Nyanaponika, on the heart of Buddhist meditation.

106
00:11:16,269 --> 00:11:19,274
Well, actually, no, it's in his later book, The Vision of the Dhamma.

107
00:11:20,034 --> 00:11:21,537
So Nyanaponika was a German monk.

108
00:11:21,797 --> 00:11:28,404
He started off the Pali, the Buddhist Publication Society, up in Kandy.

109
00:11:29,065 --> 00:11:35,332
And he wrote two very good books, one of which, The Heart of Buddhist Meditation, is still probably a classic on it.

110
00:11:35,352 --> 00:11:35,452
Yeah.

111
00:11:36,934 --> 00:11:42,964
And very luckily he practiced the Mahasi system, so I was pushed off.

112
00:11:42,984 --> 00:11:57,203
But in the vision of the Dharma, he goes on about equanimity being the primary virtue, because it's equanimity that keeps everything in control, you see.

113
00:11:57,585 --> 00:12:00,589
So when love comes, it stops it going into attachment.

114
00:12:00,688 --> 00:12:04,173
When compassion comes, it stops it going to grief and so on.

115
00:12:08,238 --> 00:12:12,467
So what was this model that the Buddha offered us?

116
00:12:13,971 --> 00:12:21,207
So there's a few ways of looking at our experience which gives us a sort of angle.

117
00:12:22,169 --> 00:12:25,216
The one is the most static experience.

118
00:12:25,736 --> 00:12:34,571
If you were to slice one moment of life, then you'd end up with what he called the five candas, five aggregates, five heaps.

119
00:12:35,191 --> 00:12:35,952
It's a still.

120
00:12:37,595 --> 00:12:47,630
And what he's doing is deconstructing everything, not simply for the joy of deconstruction, but to show us exactly where the problem lies.

121
00:12:48,171 --> 00:12:53,178
So when it comes to the body, it's a given.

122
00:12:54,913 --> 00:13:00,743
What the body offers us is within the construct of the body.

123
00:13:00,763 --> 00:13:02,985
It has its own intelligence, you might say.

124
00:13:03,687 --> 00:13:10,657
All these millions of cells that we've got, they all know what to do, don't they?

125
00:13:10,677 --> 00:13:15,183
We don't have to get in there and educate them, train them, breathe.

126
00:13:17,527 --> 00:13:19,028
It's like they know.

127
00:13:19,070 --> 00:13:29,626
And what we come to recognize about the body is that our knowledge of it is very superficial, isn't it?

128
00:13:29,647 --> 00:13:30,708
I mean, direct knowledge.

129
00:13:32,010 --> 00:13:35,456
We know from diagrams and all that about what's happening in the body.

130
00:13:35,596 --> 00:13:41,846
But as a direct experience of the body, there's very little we know, isn't there?

131
00:13:43,496 --> 00:13:54,770
I mean, have you any intimation at this present moment that the marrow in your bone is creating white blood clots?

132
00:13:54,791 --> 00:13:55,652
See, I haven't a clue.

133
00:13:57,153 --> 00:13:59,897
I haven't a clue what my liver's doing, but it feels alright.

134
00:14:02,640 --> 00:14:10,289
See, all these synapses in the brain which work at, so they tell us, quantum physical level, I haven't a clue.

135
00:14:10,309 --> 00:14:11,951
All I know is my memory's going.

136
00:14:12,370 --> 00:14:16,217
That's for sure.

137
00:14:16,238 --> 00:14:24,615
So it's recognizing that we're sort of aliens in this body, strangers within our own body.

138
00:14:25,115 --> 00:14:26,298
And it's a vehicle, isn't it?

139
00:14:26,379 --> 00:14:28,202
It's a vehicle that we're in.

140
00:14:30,025 --> 00:14:33,754
But we are aware of the sensations it gives us.

141
00:14:34,004 --> 00:14:36,389
We're aware of sensations that come from it.

142
00:14:36,409 --> 00:14:41,861
We're aware of the light that hits the eye and creates pictures for us and the sounds that strike the ear.

143
00:14:42,965 --> 00:14:50,341
We're aware at that point where the body comes in contact with the mind or the other way the mind comes in contact with the body.

144
00:14:53,511 --> 00:15:03,046
And at that point, there is the body, there must be some sort of feeling at some sort of sense door, whether it's sight or touch.

145
00:15:03,966 --> 00:15:05,408
There has to be some perception.

146
00:15:06,149 --> 00:15:15,143
So the perception is the mental image that we have of what's happening and it creates our memories and goes on to create our concepts and thought patterns.

147
00:15:17,245 --> 00:15:19,889
So those are all, these are all separate heaps.

148
00:15:20,711 --> 00:15:23,215
You've got all this stuff coming from the body, a sensation.

149
00:15:24,629 --> 00:15:30,256
Then you have it defined by the mind as being pleasant or unpleasant.

150
00:15:30,317 --> 00:15:31,999
Those are how we define it.

151
00:15:34,543 --> 00:15:37,025
And then you have these perceptual faculty going on.

152
00:15:37,385 --> 00:15:38,989
All that, you might say, is all a given.

153
00:15:40,951 --> 00:15:43,333
It all happens in one single moment.

154
00:15:45,937 --> 00:15:52,527
And then there's these sankaras, which are the mental stuff that comes up, the thought and emotional life we have.

155
00:15:53,182 --> 00:15:57,826
And the reason he separates that out is because this we have power over.

156
00:15:57,846 --> 00:16:09,778
This is where our power, in terms of how we, the atmosphere within us, what we call our emotional life, states of mind, this is where we can do something, at our sankharas.

157
00:16:11,340 --> 00:16:18,667
And then there's this magic of the mind which creates a picture for us, the cognition, the act of cognition, like a television screen.

158
00:16:19,327 --> 00:16:19,408
See?

159
00:16:21,667 --> 00:16:30,158
So that, in a sense, gives us a sort of slice, but it doesn't tell us, it doesn't tell us the movement, it doesn't give us a timeline of how these things come together.

160
00:16:31,782 --> 00:16:35,267
And that's what he does with the dependent origination.

161
00:16:35,908 --> 00:16:51,149
So, using the khandhas, using these five different types of experiences, using these five categories, that's also a way of undermining the idea that what I am is some sort of...

162
00:16:51,129 --> 00:16:52,332
entity

163
00:16:55,264 --> 00:17:01,094
some sort of wholeness, see, not a composite.

164
00:17:01,855 --> 00:17:08,044
As I look deeply I see what I'm experiencing is a composite, it's made up of this and that and this and that.

165
00:17:09,025 --> 00:17:13,231
And that undermines the idea of this body being a me or a self.

166
00:17:13,592 --> 00:17:20,402
It undermines the idea that the mind with its thoughts and emotions is a me, a mine or a self.

167
00:17:20,422 --> 00:17:24,428
In itself it's not a self.

168
00:17:30,112 --> 00:17:32,454
Now why would you want to do that?

169
00:17:32,474 --> 00:17:39,845
I mean it was pretty miserable before and now that I've discovered I'm not what I'm supposed to be or I appear to be it's even more miserable.

170
00:17:41,468 --> 00:17:42,588
What's the point of doing that?

171
00:17:42,930 --> 00:17:43,009
See?

172
00:17:43,671 --> 00:17:51,721
So the whole point is that we are taking our identity into a higher sort of place.

173
00:17:51,741 --> 00:17:57,309
So I'm using identity now in the sense of realizing who we really are or what we really are.

174
00:17:59,031 --> 00:17:59,712
So

175
00:18:01,059 --> 00:18:30,222
it's a case of stepping back from everything pulling ourselves out of everything to be able to say well I'm not that I'm not that I'm not that and eventually you see you come to realize who you are it's like walking backwards to a cliff at some point you're gonna fall off that falling off is the liberation from what you thought you were when we're in meditation when we're looking at what's coming up you see

176
00:18:31,132 --> 00:18:33,576
The looking is looking at what it's not.

177
00:18:34,758 --> 00:18:42,229
As soon as you're looking at something, at something, it can't be that what's looking.

178
00:18:42,328 --> 00:18:43,250
It becomes an object.

179
00:18:45,734 --> 00:18:47,297
Yeah.

180
00:18:47,317 --> 00:18:48,618
Not too mystifying.

181
00:18:48,638 --> 00:18:49,140
Be an object.

182
00:18:50,352 --> 00:19:01,107
If you go back to childhood, to our early months, we're told that the first couple, two or three months, four months or something, it's just one bath of sensations.

183
00:19:01,148 --> 00:19:02,911
There's no objectivity in it.

184
00:19:03,692 --> 00:19:07,018
And then out of that looms our first object, mother.

185
00:19:08,640 --> 00:19:10,903
Something looms out.

186
00:19:10,923 --> 00:19:17,153
And then, over a period of time, the whole world becomes out there, and I'm here.

187
00:19:17,992 --> 00:19:19,978
and I associate entirely with this body.

188
00:19:20,940 --> 00:19:25,592
So that process of separation, you see, all we're doing is taking that inward.

189
00:19:27,155 --> 00:19:29,521
It's a slow process of separating from everything.

190
00:19:34,784 --> 00:19:42,715
Now, in dependent origination, the psychology which produces the suffering in our lives.

191
00:19:42,955 --> 00:19:49,846
When I say suffering, remember, I'm really pointing to anything which is a slight discomfort to the most existential angst you can think about.

192
00:19:50,426 --> 00:19:52,589
It's the whole gamut of human misery.

193
00:19:52,569 --> 00:20:22,105
that's dukkha, wherever you find misery or unhappiness or even the slightest discomfort like when you're watching TV and you've got to shift your position because you feel slightly uncomfortable that's dukkha, the whole thing is dukkha it's a big word and it's his core concept he says eventually remember all I'm teaching is dukkha and the end of it is dukkha so independence origination

194
00:20:24,176 --> 00:20:28,564
at the point of, shall we say, this moment, you find these listed.

195
00:20:28,923 --> 00:20:29,965
So the body and mind.

196
00:20:30,606 --> 00:20:31,788
These are two different things.

197
00:20:32,449 --> 00:20:34,271
The body is not the mind, the mind is not the body.

198
00:20:34,613 --> 00:20:40,441
And yet, are completely dissolved in each other.

199
00:20:41,603 --> 00:20:44,287
They only separate at death.

200
00:20:44,467 --> 00:20:46,830
This is the theory.

201
00:20:46,851 --> 00:20:49,375
They only separate at death.

202
00:20:49,394 --> 00:20:51,518
And the mind which is in the body,

203
00:20:52,595 --> 00:20:58,371
can only know what the body offers it at this point of contact.

204
00:20:58,391 --> 00:21:08,156
The mind has the body, the mind and body, and there's the six senses, but this includes the mind, as a sensing organ.

205
00:21:09,722 --> 00:21:18,453
And then you have, with the body-mind you have consciousness, this ability to create pictures in the mind, whole pictures.

206
00:21:19,935 --> 00:21:25,242
You've got consciousness, body-mind, the six senses, and then you've got this contact.

207
00:21:25,262 --> 00:21:30,229
