00:42:22,317 --> 00:42:23,358
But that's not the end game.

424
00:42:23,679 --> 00:42:29,588
Even that self is a false self, but at least it's a damn sight more peaceful.

425
00:42:29,608 --> 00:42:35,797
If we can hang on there, no matter what's happening down here, there's not that much suffering going on.

426
00:42:35,818 --> 00:42:42,068
In fact, if you maintain that clarity, again, we find there's no suffering.

427
00:42:42,088 --> 00:42:42,688
It's unpleasant.

428
00:42:42,728 --> 00:42:44,831
It may be unpleasant, but there's no suffering.

429
00:42:46,903 --> 00:43:15,476
and that's the reason why we need to continuously bring ourselves back to this position of the observer now when we're actually in the process of action when we're doing something having put the right intention

430
00:43:16,942 --> 00:43:36,405
into the work, whatever work you're doing, having put the right intention into the work, and then devoting yourself to that task, just to doing that task fully, body, heart and mind, there may be moments of self-awareness, me doing something.

431
00:43:36,425 --> 00:43:38,987
But that's a false state, in the sense there's a split there.

432
00:43:39,429 --> 00:43:42,773
There's a moment of doing and a moment of watching myself doing.

433
00:43:42,793 --> 00:43:44,755
That's not meditation in action.

434
00:43:45,139 --> 00:43:54,233
I mean, it'll do, not a bad place to be, but it's not meditation in action, not the clarity of pure meditation in action.

435
00:43:54,255 --> 00:43:59,842
But as you keep devoting yourself to the task, there's a loss of a sense of self, and that is just the doing.

436
00:44:00,905 --> 00:44:12,143
And then one finishes the task, or one wakes up again to this self-awareness, and there's been a time when there hasn't been that self-awareness, and there's been a time when there's been no awareness of time.

437
00:44:13,101 --> 00:44:19,110
So time is a concept that arises with the self.

438
00:44:20,612 --> 00:44:24,277
That period has been a period of liberation from suffering.

439
00:44:26,081 --> 00:44:31,548
These are all little indications, little touches upon the Nibbanic mind, upon the Nibbanic consciousness.

440
00:44:35,797 --> 00:44:38,621
So it's not as though Nibbāna isn't there.

441
00:44:38,641 --> 00:44:40,344
It's not as though you're trying to achieve it.

442
00:44:40,385 --> 00:44:43,009
It's not as though it's like you're going from here to Dublin.

443
00:44:45,353 --> 00:44:49,079
And Dublin manufactures itself as you're going towards Dublin.

444
00:44:49,099 --> 00:44:53,585
Nibbāna's already here because what Nibbāna is is a different relationship.

445
00:44:53,965 --> 00:44:56,210
It's a relationship which doesn't have this split of a self.

446
00:44:59,954 --> 00:45:03,561
So there's your contrast between samsāra and Nibbāna.

447
00:45:05,835 --> 00:45:21,043
to do with our relationship to the particular life we're leading and to what happens within that life and to what happens within us and the process of liberation is to change that relationship

448
00:45:27,891 --> 00:45:37,007
So when this man says to the Buddha, this training you've given us, it's very hard, it's a bit tough.

449
00:45:37,027 --> 00:45:39,311
He says, well, it is.

450
00:45:39,331 --> 00:45:41,333
But in the end, he says, you achieve nirvana.

451
00:45:42,916 --> 00:45:45,239
And the questioner says, yeah, nirvana, so what?

452
00:45:47,324 --> 00:45:52,532
He says, well, when you get to nirvana, you are contented and with it happy.

453
00:45:53,844 --> 00:46:22,485
contentment is the state of no desire there's no false desire a place of absolute contentment and with it happy and happiness can be described in its various modalities of how you relate to what's happening so sometimes it's love sometimes it's compassion sometimes it's joy sometimes equanimity and there's a whole gamut of mental states that arise

454
00:46:26,380 --> 00:46:37,971
So, in the process what we discover is that the only thing that's lost, the only thing in the Buddha's words that's annihilated is this greed, hatred and delusion.

455
00:46:38,992 --> 00:46:49,682
And all the energy that was once malevolent within us, you know, these anxieties and excitements and all that, they're all transformed.

456
00:46:50,483 --> 00:46:52,184
All that energy, it's not lost.

457
00:46:57,396 --> 00:47:09,989
So probably in his early life the Buddha would enter into all sorts of discussions which seems to have been the past time of the day about philosophy and Moksha and liberation and all that with passing ascetics.

458
00:47:10,088 --> 00:47:17,436
And when he went out to practice he came to the point where he dropped his mind, the thinking mind.

459
00:47:18,257 --> 00:47:19,619
But that wasn't the end of his thinking mind.

460
00:47:20,579 --> 00:47:25,123
As soon as the liberation came, the awakened mind came, he had to work it out.

461
00:47:25,644 --> 00:47:27,065
He had to tell himself what he knew.

462
00:47:30,521 --> 00:47:38,014
He had to describe to himself what it was, how it was before he was, when he was deluded.

463
00:47:38,554 --> 00:47:39,998
And that's the wheel going one way.

464
00:47:40,478 --> 00:47:43,063
And what you do when you want to be undeluded.

465
00:47:43,963 --> 00:47:44,605
Let the thinking out.

466
00:47:45,427 --> 00:47:46,367
And then he starts teaching.

467
00:47:46,889 --> 00:47:52,458
So the very same faculty of thought now becomes a servant to the Dharma.

468
00:47:53,340 --> 00:47:54,121
He's not lost anything.

469
00:47:54,422 --> 00:47:55,804
If anything, he's gained clarity.

470
00:47:57,336 --> 00:48:00,302
So you don't lose anything by the process.

471
00:48:00,322 --> 00:48:08,436
Everything is purified, clarified, and the heart begins to live in a deeper peace, deeper happiness.

472
00:48:16,851 --> 00:48:17,572
And that's it.

473
00:48:19,931 --> 00:48:45,248
we made it so you've got these three things that we have to be working at yeah the first is to spend some time if we can every day just letting the heart speak its problem you're just sitting with it patiently the other heart the other bit is to develop the beauty of the mind how beautiful the mind can be through the practice of vipassana through the through the process of work as service

474
00:48:46,594 --> 00:48:48,376
All that reflects back on the mind.

475
00:48:48,476 --> 00:48:51,380
I mean, you've got it there in the Eightfold Path, Right Livelihood.

476
00:48:52,561 --> 00:49:03,034
I mean, apart from obvious stuff like trafficking human beings, virtually all jobs that society offers us are fine.

477
00:49:03,755 --> 00:49:09,260
It's to do with our attitude to them and how we use them to develop goodwill.

478
00:49:11,282 --> 00:49:39,804
and then there's this other bit of undermining our essential delusion through the practice of Vipassana and he does that by giving us these models of how to look at our experience which may be different from Western models so it's beginning to see our experience through the Buddha's eyes through the models of these aggregates

479
00:49:39,869 --> 00:49:44,994
and the Wheel of Dependent Regeneration, that we're tackling this problem of suffering.

480
00:49:45,014 --> 00:49:46,317
It's not a total psychology.

481
00:49:46,336 --> 00:49:48,438
There's no developmental psychology there.

482
00:49:49,740 --> 00:49:55,628
It's concerned entirely and solely with this problem of suffering.

483
00:49:56,309 --> 00:50:00,954
It doesn't deny other psychologies that have the truth in themselves.

484
00:50:01,054 --> 00:50:05,260
It doesn't deny therapies that are of assistance.

485
00:50:06,300 --> 00:50:09,824
But it's very arrow-headed towards this problem of suffering

486
00:50:26,021 --> 00:50:29,213
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

487
00:50:29,233 --> 00:50:34,512
May you be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

